
[1]flattery

   FLAT'TERY, n.

   1. False praise; commendation bestowed for the purpose of gaining favor
   and influence, or to accomplish some purpose. Direct flattery consists
   in praising a person himself; indirect flattery consists in praising a
   person through his works or his connections.

   Simple pride for flattery makes demands.

   Just praise is only a debt, but flattery is a present.

   2. Adulation; obsequiousness; wheedling.

   3. Just commendation which gratifies self-love.
